{"title_page": "Roc Alexander", "text_new": " \n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image= \n|number=45, 22\n|position=[[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1981|9|23}}\n|birth_place=Colorado Springs, Colorado\n|height_ft=5\n|height_in=10\n|weight_lbs=190\n|college=[[Washington Huskies football|Washington]]\n|undraftedyear=2004\n|pastteams=\n* [[Denver Broncos]] (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Houston Texans]] (2006\u20132007)\n|nfl=ALE577024\n}}\n'''Narond Adrian \"Roc\" Alexander''' (born September 23, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]]. He was originally signed by the [[Denver Broncos]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2004. He played [[college football]] at the [[Washington Huskies football|University of Washington]].\n\n==Early years==\nPlaying [[running back]] on [[Offense (sports)|offense]] and cornerback on [[Defense (sport)|defense]], Roc Alexander helped lead [[Roy J. Wasson High School]] of Colorado Springs to a 7-4 finish and the Metro North championship as a senior. He rushed for 1,620 yards on 162 carries (10.0 avg.) with 18 touchdowns while catching 11 passes for 274 yards (24.9 avg.). Defensively, he recorded 110 tackles and returned two interceptions for scores. In 1999, Alexander was a ''[[Denver Post]]'' \"Blue Chip\" selection, named to the ''[[Colorado Springs Gazette-Telegraph]]'' 's All-Area team, selected to the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' ' all-state squad and was an honorable mention pick on ''[[USA Today]]'' 's All-USA team. Alexander was Colorado\u2019s state champion in the [[100 m|100 meter dash]] (10.5 seconds) at Wasson.\n\n==College career==\nAlexander started 14-of-35 career games at the University of Washington, recording 86 tackles (58 solo), four interceptions, 18 passes defensed and three forced fumbles. He also added 34 kick returns for 868 yards (25.5 avg.) and a touchdown. The 25.5-yard career kick-return average ranked third all-time in UW annals, and his kick-return career yardage total ranked fourth in school annals. As a senior, he led the Huskies in kickoff returns with 268 yards on 13 returns (20.6 avg.) while contributing 25 tackles and a forced fumble on defense. He started the first five games of the season and the [[Apple Cup]] (vs. Washington State) before missing four games in the middle of the year with the same shoulder injury that forced him to miss the final seven games of 2002.  Alexander netted three of the 25 longest kickoff returns in Washington history during the 2001 season, leading the [[Pac-10 Conference]] (6th among all [[NCAA]] players) with a 29.2 kickoff return average. Additionally, he tied for sixth in the conference with four interceptions and broke up 11 passes to tie [[Chico Fraley]] (1990) for the third-best single-season mark in UW history. Alexander became just the eighth player in Washington annals to score multiple [[special teams]] touchdowns in the same year (2001), returning a fourth-quarter blocked field goal 77 yards for the go-ahead score against [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] and returning a kick 95 yards for a touchdown against [[University of Idaho|Idaho]].\n\n==NFL career==\nAlexander is perhaps best remembered for a playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Peyton Manning]], when Manning repeatedly threw to [[Reggie Wayne]] as the Colts went on to win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20050110/news_1s10replay.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207154934/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20050110/news_1s10replay.html |archive-date=2016-02-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.denverbroncos.com/page.php?id=498&contentID=2493 Denver Broncos bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040604155804/http://gohuskies.collegesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/alexander_roc00.html Washington bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander, Roc}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Houston Texans players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Colorado Springs, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies football players]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n", "text_old": " \n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image= \n|number=45, 22\n|position=[[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1981|9|23}}\n|birth_place=Colorado Springs, Colorado\n|height_ft=5\n|height_in=10\n|weight_lbs=190\n|college=[[Washington Huskies football|Washington]]\n|undraftedyear=2004\n|pastteams=\n* [[Denver Broncos]] (2004\u20132005)\n* [[Houston Texans]] (2006\u20132007)\n|nfl=ALE577024\n}}\n'''Narond Adrian \"Roc\" Alexander''' (born September 23, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]]. He was originally signed by the [[Denver Broncos]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2004. He played [[college football]] at the [[Washington Huskies football|University of Washington]].\n\n==Early years==\nPlaying [[running back]] on [[Offense (sports)|offense]] and cornerback on [[Defense (sport)|defense]], Roc Alexander helped lead [[Roy J. Wasson High School]] of Colorado Springs to a 7-4 finish and the Metro North championship as a senior. He rushed for 1,620 yards on 162 carries (10.0 avg.) with 18 touchdowns while catching 11 passes for 274 yards (24.9 avg.). Defensively, he recorded 110 tackles and returned two interceptions for scores. In 1999, Alexander was a ''[[Denver Post]]'' \"Blue Chip\" selection, named to the ''[[Colorado Springs Gazette-Telegraph]]'' 's All-Area team, selected to the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' ' all-state squad and was an honorable mention pick on ''[[USA Today]]'' 's All-USA team. Alexander was Colorado\u2019s state champion in the [[100 m|100 meter dash]] (10.5 seconds) at Wasson.\n\n==College career==\nAlexander started 14-of-35 career games at the University of Washington, recording 86 tackles (58 solo), four interceptions, 18 passes defensed and three forced fumbles. He also added 34 kick returns for 868 yards (25.5 avg.) and a touchdown. The 25.5-yard career kick-return average ranked third all-time in UW annals, and his kick-return career yardage total ranked fourth in school annals. As a senior, he led the Huskies in kickoff returns with 268 yards on 13 returns (20.6 avg.) while contributing 25 tackles and a forced fumble on defense. He started the first five games of the season and the [[Apple Cup]] (vs. Washington State) before missing four games in the middle of the year with the same shoulder injury that forced him to miss the final seven games of 2002.  Alexander netted three of the 25 longest kickoff returns in Washington history during the 2001 season, leading the [[Pac-10 Conference]] (6th among all [[NCAA]] players) with a 29.2 kickoff return average. Additionally, he tied for sixth in the conference with four interceptions and broke up 11 passes to tie [[Chico Fraley]] (1990) for the third-best single-season mark in UW history. Alexander became just the eighth player in Washington annals to score multiple [[special teams]] touchdowns in the same year (2001), returning a fourth-quarter blocked field goal 77 yards for the go-ahead score against [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] and returning a kick 95 yards for a touchdown against [[University of Idaho|Idaho]].\n\n==NFL career==\nAlexander is perhaps best remembered for a playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Peyton Manning]], when Manning repeatedly threw to [[Reggie Wayne]] as the Colts went on to win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20050110/news_1s10replay.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207154934/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20050110/news_1s10replay.html |archive-date=2016-02-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Rape allegations==\nRoc Alexander has been accused by at least two different individuals of sexually assaulting them.<ref>[https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/uw-huskies/jury-upholds-uw-in-handling-of-rape-allegation-against-ex-player/]</ref> The lawsuits filed against him claim that the University of Washington athletics department pressured the complainants to withdraw their allegations, in order to avoid negative publicity and the possibility of Roc Alexander leaving UW for another university if suspended.<ref>https://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/UW-forced-to-defend-actions-in-alleged-rape-1264178.php</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.denverbroncos.com/page.php?id=498&contentID=2493 Denver Broncos bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040604155804/http://gohuskies.collegesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/alexander_roc00.html Washington bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander, Roc}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Houston Texans players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Colorado Springs, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies football players]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n", "name_user": "2600:387:a:19::4e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Stop bashing this guy name.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roc_Alexander"}
{"title_page": "2004 League of Ireland First Division", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| competition      = [[League of Ireland First Division]]\n| season           = 2004\n| winners          = [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]\n| promoted         = [[University College Dublin A.F.C.|UCD]]<br>[[Bray Wanderers A.F.C.|Bray Wanderers]]\n| league topscorer = [[Kevin McHugh]]: 22 (2) <br>([[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]])<ref name=\"rsssftop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/iertops.html |title=Ireland - List of Topscorers |publisher=www.rsssf.com |accessdate=6 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406093820/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/iertops.html |archivedate=6 April 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"rsssf2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ier04.html|title=Ireland 2004|publisher=www.rsssf.com|accessdate=16 July 2016|date= }}</ref>\n| biggest home win = \n| biggest away win = \n| highest scoring  = \n| matches          = \n| total goals      = \n| prevseason = [[2003 League of Ireland First Division|2003]]\n| nextseason = [[2005 League of Ireland First Division|2005]]\n}}\nThe '''2004 League of Ireland First Division''' season was the 20th season of the [[League of Ireland First Division]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe First Division was contested by 12 teams and [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]] won the division. Each team played the other teams three times, totalling 33 games. The [[2005 League of Ireland Premier Division|2005]]  season would see the [[League of Ireland Premier Division]] revert to 12 twelve teams. To facilitate this expansion there was no promotion/relegation play-off this season and the second and third placed teams, [[University College Dublin A.F.C.|UCD]] and [[Bray Wanderers A.F.C.|Bray Wanderers]], were automatically promoted.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite book|last=Graham|first=Alex|title=Football in the Republic of Ireland a Statistical Record 1921